## EC2 Instance Connect

I connected to my EC2 instance using EC2 Instance Connect, an alternative to SSH. Instance Connect lets me securely connect to my EC2 instances directly from the AWS Management Console. I'm still using SSH, but with all the key management handling it's handled for me. This takes away a lot of the complexity of setting up SSH.

My first attempt at gaining direct access to my public server resulted in an error because I had not configured the correct inbound rules for both the public and private security groups.

I fixed this error by configuring the public security group's inbound rule to allow SSH traffic from anywhere (IPv4). While this is not considered the best security practice, it is acceptable for the scope of this project.

I also configured the private security group's inbound rule to allow TCP traffic from the public security group (using a custom security group rule). This configuration enables the instances to communicate with each other while still preventing direct public access to the private instance.

